  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under U.S. federal law, money laundering is a serious offense with significant penalties. The specific penalties depend on the amount of money involved, the nature of the underlying criminal activity, and other factors. Here are the key penalties outlined in the **Money Laundering Control Act** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957) and related statutes:\n\n### **Criminal Penalties:**\n1. **Prison Sentences:**\n   - Individuals convicted of money laundering can face up to **20 years in federal prison** for each offense under 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956.\n   - If the offense involves proceeds from certain serious crimes (e.g., drug trafficking or terrorism), the maximum sentence can increase to **25 years**.\n   - For violations of 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957 (engaging in monetary transactions with criminally derived property), the maximum sentence is **10 years**.\n\n2. **Fines:**\n   - The fines can be substantial, with a maximum of **$500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction**, whichever is greater.\n   - For organizations, fines can reach **$1 million or twice the value of the property involved**.\n\n3. **Forfeiture:**\n   - The government can seize and forfeit any property involved in or derived from the money laundering offense, including funds, assets, and even businesses.\n\n4. **Enhanced Penalties:**\n   - If the money laundering involves proceeds from violations of the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)**, **Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA)**, or other federal crimes, additional penalties may apply.\n   - Involvement in money laundering schemes with connections to terrorism can result in even harsher penalties, including life imprisonment in some cases.\n\n---\n\n### **Civil Penalties:**\n- **Financial Institutions:** Financial institutions that fail to comply with anti-money laundering (AML) regulations, such as failing to file suspicious activity reports (SARs) or maintain proper records, can face hefty fines. Civil penalties can range from **$25,000 to $100,000 per violation**, depending on the severity.\n- **Individuals:** Individuals involved in money laundering may also face civil fines, which can be substantial.\n\n---\n\n### **Collateral Consequences:**\n- **Reputational Damage:** Convictions for money laundering can severely damage personal and professional reputations.\n- **Loss of Licenses:** Professionals (e.g., bankers, lawyers, accountants) convicted of money laundering may lose their professional licenses.\n- **Immigration Consequences:** Non-U.S. citizens convicted of money laundering may face deportation or inadmissibility to the U.S.\n\n---\n\n### **Key Statutes:**\n- **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956:** Prohibits laundering money derived from specified unlawful activities (SUAs).\n- **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957:** Prohibits engaging in financial transactions involving criminally derived property exceeding $10,000.\n- **31 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 5311\u20135332 (Bank Secrecy Act):** Requires financial institutions to report and maintain records of certain transactions to prevent money laundering.\n\nThese penalties underscore the federal government\u2019s commitment to combating money laundering and related financial crimes. If you or someone you know is facing such charges, consulting with a qualified criminal defense attorney is essential to navigate the complexities of these cases.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
